For this exercise, we will use the annual Worlds bank US GDP (Gross domestic product) 1960 2017 dataset (Data set: usgdp.rda).

  1. Load the usgdp.rda dataset and split it into a training dataset (1960 - 2012) and a test dataset (2013 - 2017)
# Load the data
load(file = "usgdp.rda")
data  <- ts(usgdp$GDP, start = 1960)
train <- window(data, start = 1960, end = 2012)
test  <- window(data, start = 2013, end = 2017)
  1. Plot the training dataset. Is the Box-Cox transformation necessary for this data?
autoplot(train)

Yes, it is necessary. The curve is a little bit convave up, and it shows increasing variantion as the level of the series increases. Thus, we need the Box-Cox transformation to stabilize the variance.

# to balance the seasonal fluctuations and random variation across the series.
lambda <- BoxCox.lambda(train)
lambda
## [1] 0.2310656
# Re-plot the training data after Box-Cox transformation
train %>% BoxCox(lambda = 0.2310656) %>% autoplot()

  1. Plot the 1st and 2nd order difference of the data. Apply KPSS Test for Stationarity to determine which difference order results in a stationary dataset.
plot(diff(train, differences = 1))

kpss.test(diff(train, differences = 1))
## Warning in kpss.test(diff(train, differences = 1)): p-value smaller than printed
## p-value
## 
##  KPSS Test for Level Stationarity
## 
## data:  diff(train, differences = 1)
## KPSS Level = 1.1194, Truncation lag parameter = 3, p-value = 0.01
plot(diff(train, differences = 2))

kpss.test(diff(train, differences = 2))
## Warning in kpss.test(diff(train, differences = 2)): p-value greater than printed
## p-value
## 
##  KPSS Test for Level Stationarity
## 
## data:  diff(train, differences = 2)
## KPSS Level = 0.030686, Truncation lag parameter = 3, p-value = 0.1

According to the KPSS result, the p-value of the 1st order difference is 0.01 and that of the 2nd order difference is 0.1. Since the test statistic of 1nd KPSS is much smaller than the 2nd one, and it is smaller than 0.05, we can reject the null hypothesis and say that the 1st differenced data is not stationary. For the 2nd differenced data, the p-value is greater than 0.05. Thus, we cannot reject the null hypothesis, which means the 2nd differenced data can be concluded as stationary.

  1. Fit a suitable ARIMA model to the training dataset using the auto.arima() function. Remember to transform the data first if necessary. Report the resulting ,, and the coefficients values.
